EMERGE_DEFAULT_OPTS="--jobs=1 --load-average=1"

# MAKEOPTS - set -j# and -l#
#  -j (--jobs) is the number of simultaneous jobs (basic recommendation is (2 * #cpus) + 1)
#     (note: total #cpus can be high, in a distcc environment)
#  -l (--load-average) limits creation of parallel tasks based on the current load average
#     (do not count remote cpus; basic recommendation is #cpus +1 )
# former (now obsolete) wisdom from the 2006 timeframe:
# aggressive setting --
#   MAKEOPTS=" -j$(( $(( 2 * $(nproc) )) + 1 )) -l$(( $(nproc) + 1 ))"
#   MAKEOPTS="-j9 -l5"  # example for 4 core system (no remote distcc support)
# Above method is now obsolete; for example, as of 2026 --
#   gcc/clang may take 1.5 GB to 2 GB of RAM per job; rustc can use 3–6 GB;
#   linkers can use 8–16 GB on large packages
# To avoid swap storms and OOM kills, limit jobs to RAM/2GB
#   per job. Lower the MAKEOPTS j value to provide at least 2G RAM per cpu, so the system can
#   compile without hitting swap very often, slowing things down
# Also, the -l parameter is meaningless for distcc clients, so ignore it
# Conserviative setting -- jobs must be integer, so integer division is sufficient
#   memtotal_kb=$(awk '/MemTotal/ {print $2}' /proc/meminfo)
#   jobs=$(( memtotal_kb / (2 * 1024 * 1024) ))
#   [ $jobs -lt 1 ] && jobs=1
#   MAKEOPTS="-j${jobs}"
# For DISTCC clients the 2026 wisdom after years of tuning is
#   consider local capacity L = min(local_cores, local_ram/2G)
#   consider remote capacity R = sum(min(remote_cores, remote_ram_gb / 2))
#   MAKEOPTS = -j(L + floor(R * 0.75))  # this is the formula used by
#     Gentoo distcc maintainers, ChromiumOS build farms, Yocto build clusters,
#     Armbian’s old distcc scripts, etc.  Note: the 0.75 accounts for
#     network latency, preprocessing bottlenecks, which are inherently local,
#     occasional remote host stall, and need to always leave local RAM "headroom"
# Default MAKEOPTS for joetoo deployments -
MAKEOPTS=-j3
